        template: "expected closing brace to end a block, found {found}",
        explain: "The parser expected a closing brace `}` to end a block expression. Without it, the parser may silently consume the next top-level item into the prior body. Stage1 punch list Gap 5 — added so block-close mismatches surface as a precise S0 diagnostic instead of a downstream cascade. Note: braces are escaped from the message template here because `compiler/diag/builder.hexa::_interpolate` treats raw `{...}` as a placeholder boundary.",
        fix_it_kind: FixItKind::Insert
    },
    DiagSpec {
        code: "HX0013",
        title: "array literal too large for the compile path",
        severity: Severity::Error,
        stage: "S0",
        template: "array literal has {found} elements — exceeds the compile-path cap (1024). Construct at runtime (loop + push) or load via the atlas.n6 SSOT (n6/atlas.n6 + compiler/atlas/merger.hexa). (HXC sidecar path retired 2026-05-22 — PRs #312 + #314.)",
        explain: "GRAMMAR-ENFORCED real-limit (compile path only; the interpreter / self/parser.hexa is exempt and handles arbitrarily large array literals fine — proven O(1) RSS). A source-level array literal with thousands of elements (notably the embedded-atlas const arrays in compiler/atlas/embedded.gen.hexa, ~7400 AtlasNode) makes the new compiler's codegen/error-recovery accumulate super-quadratic (O(n²)) RSS — empirically 231 GiB / 52 s before OOM, the #1 blocker of stage-2/stage-3/E2. Rather than rely on runtime path selection (the prior HXC fast path still left the giant const-literal fallback in the build graph, so it was still codegen'd), the compile path STRUCTURALLY REJECTS the construct so the O(n²) is impossible by grammar, not merely avoided. Fix: build large collections at runtime, or serve them from the atlas.n6 SSOT (governance @D h_atlas_single_export; PR #312 + #314 retired the HXC sidecar 2026-05-22 — static_atlas() now parses n6/atlas.n6 via compiler/atlas/merger.hexa).",
        fix_it_kind: FixItKind::Replace
    },
